  Suggested Additional Improvements (my thoughts)

  These are things you haven't asked for but are natural companions to this work:

  1. Progress indicator during bulk historical download: When downloading 17 years (1986–2002) for the first
  time, add a Rich progress bar or at minimum print "Downloading {year} …" so the user isn't staring at a
  frozen terminal.
  2. calc_range / display_range separation at the DataFrame level: chart_display_range clips the chart axes but
   today the tables (display_instrument) always show the latest snapshot. When you're in a historical study
  mode (e.g., studying 2000–2004), you'd probably want the snapshot date to be chart_display_range.end, not
  "today". This would require a snapshot_date parameter passed through the pipeline. Worth discussing
  separately.
  3. Pre-2003 column-gap warning in terminal output: When an instrument has NaN concentration rows (pre-2004),
  the OI concentration section should say "Data not available (pre-2004)" instead of showing dashes or errors.
  4. Automatic hist_data_before_2003 activation: Instead of a separate flag, we could infer it from
  data_years_history alone (if current_year - data_years_history < 2003 → auto-activate). But having an
  explicit flag is safer and more predictable, so the current plan is fine.
  5. chart_display_range also in non-chart output: The text tables currently show a single snapshot (latest
  date). With historical range charts, users might want a "as of date" table too — i.e., show signal status at
  the end of the display range. Out of scope for now but a natural follow-on.

  ---
  Risk Areas

  - Column name drift across decades: The CFTC Legacy format is very stable, but years before ~1995 may have
  subtle differences. Should add a try/except around column mapping with a fallback that logs the available
  columns.
  - cot-reports library year minimum: The library may silently fail or return an empty DataFrame for very old
  years (1986–1990) depending on the library version. The hist_fetcher direct download path bypasses this
  entirely.
  - Encoding: CFTC .txt files use ASCII/latin-1; pd.read_csv(..., encoding='latin-1') is safest.
  - chart_display_range vs. lookback: If the display range is shorter than the lookback window, the index
  calculations are still correct (they use full data), but users may be confused seeing an index chart that
  starts before their lookback window starts. A log note about this would help.

